\par }{\b\f1\fs28\cgrid0 Part 1: Teaching with }{\b\i\f1\fs28\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\b\f1\fs28\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\i\f1\fs24\cgrid0 Introduction
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f4\fs28\cgrid0 WHAT IS }{\b\i\f4\fs28\cgrid0 SIMCITY 3000}{\b\f4\fs28\cgrid0 ?
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 
\par }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  is a city simulator\emdash a dynamic model of urban life, complete with
 simulated citizens (Sims), traffic, commerce, industry, utilities, taxes, and other important aspects of city life. Its graphic interface makes it easy enough for children to use. Its flexibility and modeling accuracy make it suitable for adults.
\par 
\par As an educational tool, }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  allows students to learn as they assume the role of mayor. In this role they will do such things as:
\par 
\par }\pard \fi-240\li720\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab Create and manage their own city.
\par 
\par \bullet \tab Determine the effect of terrain on land value.
\par 
\par \bullet \tab Investigate the relationship between industry, commerce, and residential populations.
\par 
\par \bullet \tab Compare and contrast different types of city layouts.
\par 
\par \bullet \tab Explore how technological changes affect utilities and pollution.
\par 
\par \bullet \tab Investigate ways in which to increase public safety.
\par 
\par \bullet \tab Explore the interdependencies between taxes and city management.
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab Evaluate the costs and benefits of mass transportation.
\par 
\par \bullet \tab Learn about laws and ordinances.
\par 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f4\fs28\cgrid0 OUR GOALS
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 Our primary goal as producers of educational software is to help people develop an 
understanding of complex systems by providing the means for playing with those systems. To do this, we present complex information in a game format, which makes both teaching and learning more exciting.
\par 
\par Our ultimate goal in creating }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  (and other simulations) is to inspire the player to look beyond the simulation, transferring the insight gained from playing }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0 
 to the real world. }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  illustrates what is usually abstract for students: that the real world has millions of people i
n thousands of cities with the same needs, wants and hopes, and that we should treat people, cities, the planet, and life itself with respect and care.
\par 
\par We hope that by capturing what has been, for the most part, thought of in the abstract and by giving st
udents the opportunity to participate in typically unfamiliar activities, they will not only learn about cities and city management, but will also develop a sensitivity to and appreciation of the delicate balance inherent in the real world.
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f4\fs28\cgrid0 SIMULATIONS IN THE REAL WORLD
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0 
 is part of a series of products from Maxis called System Simulations. In a System Simulation, we provide a set of rules and tools that describe, create, and control a system. Simulations such as these are increasingly powerful
 tools that allow researchers in all fields from astronomy zoology to conduct inquiries into areas where traditional laboratory methods are not possible or practical.
\par 
\par Simulations, whether they are modeling real or hypothetical situations, allow the user t
o change individual variables to see how specific changes affect systems. Unlike the real world, simulations allow individual and precise manipulation of variables involving anything from climate to the laws of physics to time itself.}{\b\f4\cgrid0 

\par 
\par }{\b\f4\fs28\cgrid0 SIMULATIONS IN EDUCATION
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
Simulations involve action and behavior rather than just the acquisition of facts. Simulations allow students to study processes instead of events. In a simulation, students explore and test new ideas; they discover what happens when principles are }{
\i\f4\cgrid0 applied}{\f4\cgrid0  to a situation, rather than merely learn about a set of facts and principles. Students become active and powerful participants in the learning process.
\par 
\par Using a computer simulation like }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  is more than a single learning experience; it is an introduction to a new tool for research.
\par 
\par }\pard \fi-240\li720\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab Simulations encourage and require imaginative thinking rather than rote learning.
\par 
\par \bullet \tab Simulations give students experience in decision-making, and allow them to quickly see the consequences of their decisions.
\par 
\par \bullet \tab Simulations allow students to become explorers that create and follow their own hypotheses rather than mere observers reading what other people have done.
\par 
\par \bullet \tab Learning becomes student-centered rather than teacher-centered.
\par 
\par \bullet \tab Simulations are particularly appropriate when the inquiry process assumes that knowledge is cumulative and constantly expanding.
\par 
\par \bullet \tab Simulations like }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  fit easily into interdisciplinary learning. In addition to its use in studying social sciences, }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0 
 can add excitement to math, statistics, ecology, history, geography, and even creative writing.
\par 
\par \bullet \tab Simulations can be used to engage both honor students and at-risk students: those with learning difficulties or short attention spans as well as those who do poorly in school because of boredom. 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 LIMITATIONS OF SIMULATIONS}{\f4\fs24\cgrid0 
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par It is important to keep in mind that while simulations offer many possibilities for creativity and inquiry, they also have limitations. Simulations, by definition, are not r
eal. As complex as any simulation is, it is nevertheless a simplified, artificial system that can in no way come close to the real world in complexity and variety.
\par 
\par Students must always be alert for limitations of simulations and for differences between th
e way systems work in their computers and the way systems work in real life. In all observations and conclusions, students should consider how the simulation's limitations may have affected their experimental design, the data they were able to collect, an
d the outcome of the experiment.
\par 
\par In general, when dealing with simulations, specific results may be inaccurate, but general trends, even with simple simulations, tend to be highly accurate.
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\fs28\cgrid0 ABOUT THE }{\b\i\f4\fs28\cgrid0 SIMCITY 3000}{\b\f4\fs28\cgrid0  TEACHER'S GUIDE
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 This Teacher's Guide is designed to help you to use }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  in your classroom with minimal preparation. As you and your students explore and play with }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0 
, you will develop your own curricular uses, connections, and applications to further the program's educational
 possibilities. When you do, we would appreciate it if you would write or e-mail us (see Part 3 for the information) and tell us about it so we can help you share your ideas with other educators.
\par 
\par This guide is divided into three parts:
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Part 1: Teaching with }{\b\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  gives a general overview of }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0 , discusses simulations in education, and describes using }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0 
 in your classroom, including the logistics of using }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  with different numbers of computers.
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Part 2: }{\b\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\b\f4\cgrid0  Simulations}{\f4\cgrid0  has three units\emdash 
each one covers a different subject area. Each unit includes a unit summary, background information, and discussion questions for the simulations in the unit. Each simulation within a unit gives the objectives for and description of
 the activity. In some cases, a simulation contains Extension Activities that expand on the information covered in the simulation. This part also contains a Getting Started section, which explains any preparations that should be done before doing the simu
lations in class.
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Part 3: Blackline Masters and Resources}{\f4\cgrid0  contains blackline masters for the first lesson in Part 2. You'll also find reference sheets that might be helpful for learning the }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0 
 controls and selected demographic and economic data for five real cities (Chicago, Houston, Miami, New York, and San Francisco). This part also includes additional resources and information about the author. 
\par 
\par The activities in this guide give a sample of the activities and subjects that can be addressed using }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0 . We hope that these activities will prepare students to formulate plans, take action, and resolve problems.

\par 
\par You can adapt the simulations and activities in this guide for use in grades 
6-12 and beyond. Reorganize the activities to suit the subject you are teaching, using them sequentially to form a teaching unit or individually as single learning experiences. Because the guide is flexible across a few grades, you may need to adjust the 
lessons slightly, tailoring them to the specific needs of your grade and subject focus.
\par 
\par }{\b\i\f1\fs24\cgrid0 Using SimCity 3000 in Your Classroom
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 
\par }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  can be used to enhance
 just about any instructional unit. It can stand alone as an enrichment computer activity, or it can be used as a pivotal activity connected to other activities and projects done before, during, or after using the computer program. Use the lessons in this
 guide to integrate }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  into your curriculum, or to create custom lessons to suit your needs. Some options for implementing }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  in the classroom include:
\par 
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 1.\tab Use }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  demonstrations or experiments to introduce a unit. Then set stud
ents loose to research the subject in other, more traditional, sources such as textbooks, films, libraries, interviews, and personal experience. After the research, repeat the same experiment (or another one or two) and the students can view it from a pos
ition of knowledge.
\par 
\par 2.\tab Use a }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  demonstration or experiment as the culminating activity for a unit, providing an opportunity for students to put theory into practice.
\par 
\par 3.\tab Use }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  as part of a unit on cities, and sponsor a city-building c
ompetition. Award prizes for the biggest, the most beautiful, the most profitable, the highest quality of life, etc. Invite other schools to compete by modem or host a competition in your school's computer lab.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 SCHEDULING CLASS TIME
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  is flexible in its time requirements. It can take as little time or as much time as you want it to. If you use this Teacher's Guide to its fullest, each unit can take up to four (or more) class periods:
\par 
\par }\pard \fi-240\li720\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab }{\f4\fs18\up6\cgrid0 1}{\f4\cgrid0 /}{\f4\fs18\dn4\cgrid0 2}{\f4\cgrid0 -1 class period for the Jumping-In Discussion.
\par 
\par \bullet \tab 1-2 class periods for the }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  simulations and questions.
\par 
\par \bullet \tab }{\f4\fs18\up6\cgrid0 1}{\f4\cgrid0 /}{\f4\fs18\dn4\cgrid0 2}{\f4\cgrid0 -1 class period for the Extension Activities.}{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 WHOLE CLASS INSTRUCTION
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 If you have access to an LCD Display for your computer and an overhead projector, the whole class can participate together in }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  activities.
\par 
\par }\pard \fi-240\li720\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab One person (student or teacher) facilitates the discussion.
\par 
\par \bullet \tab One person operates the program, using suggestions from individual students or from teams of students.
\par 
\par \bullet \tab Small groups of students take turns presenting experiments to the whole class.}{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 GROUP WORK
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 Divide the class into groups of three to five students each, assigning each group to a specific day or time with the computer. There are several ways to involve the groups:
\par 
\par }\pard \fi-240\li720\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\i\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab }{\f4\cgrid0 Individual model: Each group performs the same activity to replicate, dispute, and verify results.
\par }{\i\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab Cooperative model: Each group works on a different activity and reports the results to the class. This covers more subject matter, and allows for more individual creativity.
\par 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 INDIVIDUAL WORK
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 Have the students individually complete the }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  activities. Later, they can share their findings in groups or as a class.}{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 INDEPENDENT EXPLORATION
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 By making }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  available for individual stud
ents to use during class, before or after school, or in free time, you can help students find their own area of interest, and allow them the time to explore and be creative. Don't worry\emdash the }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0 
 environment is so rich and varied that no amount of independent play can ruin your planned lessons.}{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 COOPERATIVE/COLLABORATIVE LEARNING
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 Because }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  offers many complex interactions, you will find many opportunities to use cooperative and collaborative learning groups.
\par 
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 1.}{\i\f4\cgrid0 \tab }{\f4\cgrid0 Students will learn from one another, both about how to use }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0 
 and about the activity in which they are cooperatively engaged.}{\i\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 2.\tab Students can be assigned cooperative roles within a group. Roles can be expanded or combined depending on group size.
\par 
\par 3.\tab Collaborative groups will foster discussion and even debate about the concepts being investigated, strengthening participation in the exploration and learning process.}{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 
\par JOURNAL WRITING
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 No matter how you decide to implement }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  in your clas
sroom, you will find that there are many opportunities to integrate journal writing into the lessons. For example, as students work through the activities, you might have them record their process of discovery\emdash 
what they were trying to find out and why, wha
t steps they took, what controls and variables they used, and so on. You might also have students record their answers to the Jumping In questions in their journals, and then compare and contrast their answers with the new knowledge they gain after comple
ting the activities.
\par }{\b\f4\fs36\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f1\fs28\cgrid0 Part 2: }{\b\i\f1\fs28\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\b\f1\fs28\cgrid0  Simulations
