\par 
\par }{\b\f4\fs28\cgrid0 TEACHER AND STUDENT PREPARATION
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 1.\tab Follow the directions on the }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  reference card to install }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  on your computer(s).
\par 
\par 2.\tab You and your students won't need to take a crash course in computer literacy in order to use }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0 . As a matter of fact, you'll probably find the }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  interface very easy to un
derstand and use. However, if you want a bit more experience using }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0 , Activity 1 (Basic Building 101) in the City Planning and Design Unit gives the basics about }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0 
 so that you and your students will get the most out of the subsequent 
lessons. You can also work through the Tutorial that comes with the program. You won't need to refer to the Reference Guide or the Tutorial in order to use this guide, except for further clarification if you want it.
\par 
\par 3.\tab Some of the lessons require step-by-step procedures. When covering one of these lessons, you may want to write the steps out on a blackboard, or duplicate that portion of the lesson to distribute to each student or group.
\par 
\par 4.\tab Before your students begin the activities, you might want to put a copy of the }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  Controls reference sheets\emdash see Part 3 for the blackline masters\emdash 
on the wall for students to refer to. Or, you could simply make copies of the pages, laminate them, and place them by the computers.
\par 
\par 5.\tab If students are working on mo
re than one computer at the same time, you might want to have them all run the simulation at the same speed setting, preferably the fastest (African Swallow), so that the class as a whole proceeds more or less at the same pace.
\par 
\par 6.\tab }{\i\f4\cgrid0 Optional}{\f4\cgrid0 : You might find the Jumping In discussion before each unit's activities more interesting if you have done the activities yourself ahead of time.
\par 
\par 7.\tab }{\i\f4\cgrid0 Optional}{\f4\cgrid0 : Part 3 includes demographic and economic data on five selected cities in the United States. You may want to repr
oduce these data sheets and hand out copies for students to refer to as a basis for the Jumping In discussions before the lessons. In addition, you may want to obtain similar data for your area for comparative studies.
\par 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\fs28\cgrid0 STARTER TOWNS, SAVED CITIES, AND REAL CITY TERRAINS
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 Many of the lessons in this guide make use of three types of existing files that come with }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0 
. These files can be accessed from the Opening Screen of the game, or through the Load option in the Change Settings & Exit Menu.
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Starter Towns }{\f4\cgrid0 
are prebuilt city "templates" that are based on city planning theories from different times and different areas of the world. These templates include transportation, zones, power, water, landfills, and various civic, historical, and/or recreationa
l buildings.
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Real  City Terrains }{\f4\cgrid0 are starting terrains based on geographic data from real cities all over the world. These files do }{\i\f4\cgrid0 not}{\f4\cgrid0 
 contain any prebuilt areas. Additional real city terrains are available from the }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  web site (www.simcity.com).
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Saved Cities}{\f4\cgrid0  are established }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  cities that}{\b\f4\cgrid0  }{\f4\cgrid0 have been allowed to run for many years (SimTime). These cities not only have roads, zones, and servic
es in place, they also have a thriving population, modified budgets and ordinances, and any problems that the previous mayor may have left behind at the end of his or her term. Additional saved cities are also available from the }{\i\f4\cgrid0 
SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  web site (www.simcity.com).
\par 
\par }{\b\i\f1\fs24\cgrid0 Unit 1\emdash City Planning and Design
\par }{\f4\fs24\cgrid0 
\par }{\f1\fs24\cgrid0 Unit Summary
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par In this unit, your students will learn about some of the basic elements of city planning and design, including selection of location, zones and zone density, and availability of transportation. 
(Other aspects of city planning, such as the need for services and economic policies are covered in Units 2 and 3 of this Teacher's Guide.) First, students will use }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0 
 to build a simple city. Next, students will study the relationship between ter
rain and land value. Then students will examine the relationship between residential, industrial, and commercial zones and their impact on city development. Next, students will use }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0 
's Starter Towns to compare and contrast some of the different city layouts that city planners have used over time. Finally, students will investigate the role of transportation in city development.
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs24\cgrid0 Background
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par Cities contain a number of different elements, including housing; commercial facilities; industry; transportation; utilities; medical, government, and educational services; and recreational, cultural, and religious facilities. }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
City planning and design}{\f4\cgrid0  involves the physical arrangement of the city according to aesthetic and functional standards as well as the de
velopment of social, economic, and environmental policies to help encourage the growth and survival of the city. Modern city planners must take into account such factors as providing healthy and safe living conditions; employment opportunities; }{
\b\f4\cgrid0 zoning}{\f4\cgrid0 
 (which governs how land may be used and the size, type, and number of structures that may be built on the land); methods of transportation and proximity to transportation; types of utilities and their impact on the environment; the availability of police
,
 fire, sanitation, and other services; and the economic forces that affect a city. In addition, the development of a city must reflect the interests and priorities of the residents and businesses within the city in order to help maintain the quality of li
fe that these groups desire.
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs24\cgrid0 Jumping In
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par Below are some sample discussion questions to help you get your class talking and thinking about city planning and design. Mix, match, tailor, or add questions as you see fit to customize the discussion to your class age and grade.
\par 
\par }\pard \fi-240\li720\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab What is a city? What purpose(s) do cities have?
\par 
\par \bullet \tab Which is more important to a city: streets and buildings, or the things and people in them?
\par 
\par \bullet \tab Who designs cities? Who builds them?
\par 
\par \bullet \tab Where would you prefer to live: near water, on a hill, or on a flat, open area? Why?
\par 
\par \bullet \tab What affect might the location of a city have on the city? On the people in the city? On the industry in the city?
\par 
\par \bullet \tab What is land value? Is it important? Why or why not?
\par 
\par \bullet \tab What is zoning? Why might zoning be important in city planning?
\par 
\par \bullet \tab What is industry? Name as many industries in your town as you can and rate them for the number of people they employ, the amount of space they take up, the amount of money they make, and the amount of pollution they cause.
\par 
\par \bullet \tab What is commerce? Name as many commercial businesses in your town as you can and rate them for the number of people they employ, the amount of space they take up, the amount of money they make, and the amount of pollution they cause.
\par 
\par \bullet \tab What is the difference between an urban area and a suburban area?
\par 
\par \bullet \tab What are some of the different ways in which people can move from place to place within a city?
\par 
\par \bullet \tab Suppose you had a choice of living in one of two houses, one of which 
was close to a well-traveled road and the other of which was far from any roads or other forms of transportation. What are some of the advantages and disadvantages of each location? In which location would you prefer to live? Why? 
\par 
\par }\pard \fi-240\li240\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\fs28\cgrid0 Simulation 1: Basic Building 101
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 
\par Objectives
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-240\li720\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab To create and build a small city using }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0 .
\par \bullet \tab To familiarize students with the }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  program and some of its controls.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 The Activity
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par Make copies of the "Basic Building 101" pages (pp. 34-42) to distribute to your 
students. These pages will lead students through the process of starting the program, choosing an area in which to locate the city, zoning areas in the city, and adding power, water, and garbage facilities. (Note: This city is not intended to be a "perfec
t" city\emdash 
it does not have the correct ratio of residential, commercial, and industrial zones, for example, nor does it include government services, such as police or schools. Instead, students will be using this city in later simulations as a basis for inves
tigating these types of issues.)
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 EXTENSION
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-240\li240\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab 
Have students load Basic City (from Simulation 1: Basic Building 101). Then have them click on each button on the Main Toolbar to identify the different elements available for city building within }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0 
. Have them list the different elements on a separate piece of paper. Discuss how the different city elements in }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0 
 compare with those elements found in real cities. What elements are the same? What elements are missing? Which elements are necess
ary for city life? Which of the elements would students want to have available where they live? Why? Which of the elements would students not want near where they live? Why? 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f4\fs28\cgrid0 Simulation 2: Location, Location, Location
\par }{\f4\fs24\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 Objectives
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-240\li720\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab To investigate the effects of terrain on land value and building limitations.
\par 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 The Activity
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par In this simulation, students explore a thriving city to investigate how different elevations and water affect land value. Students will discover that land near water or at elevations higher than average have a higher land value than other areas.
\par 
\par Have students perform the following actions:
\par 
\par }\pard \fi-360\li360\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 1.\tab Start }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  and load Big Mountain City (a Saved City that comes with the program).
\par 
\par 2.\tab Click on the}{\b\f4\cgrid0  Layer Views}{\f4\cgrid0  button in the Information Bar to open the View City Layers Window. Select the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Land Value}{\f4\cgrid0  layer view from the City Layer Views Menu, and click the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Apply}
{\f4\cgrid0  button. This will display the land value of the city in the City View Window. The higher the intensity of blue, the higher the land value. Click on the checkmark to close the View City Layers Window.
\par 
\par 3.\tab Scroll around the city. Use the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Query }{\f4\cgrid0 tool to get actual land values and elevations. In general, which areas have the highest land values\emdash those near water, thos
e with higher than average elevations, those with lower than average elevations, or those on flat, open areas?
\par 
\par 4.\tab Do not save this simulation.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 FOLLOW UP}{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 : }{\f4\cgrid0 Have the students discuss the following questions
\par }\pard \fi-240\li240\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab How does terrain affect land value in }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0 ?
\par \bullet \tab What are some of the advantages of building on flat, open land? What are some of the possible disadvantages?
\par \bullet \tab What are some of the advantages of building on hills or mountains? What are some of the possible disadvantages?
\par \bullet \tab What are some of the advantages of building near water? What are some possible disadvantages?
\par \bullet \tab What type of terrain would you want for each of the following types of cities: a large, sprawling city, a city that is a trading center, a summer vacation city? Why?
\par \bullet .\tab In additional to terrain, what other factors might have an effect on land value?
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 
\par EXTENSIONS
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-240\li240\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab Have students view some of the different real city terrains that come with the program, such as San Francisco, New Orleans, Houston, and Hong Kong. Ask them to 
discuss the possible advantages and disadvantages that each terrain presents for a city planner. How might the terrain of an area affect the overall population that the area can support?
\par \bullet \tab Have students use one of the real city terrains that come with }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  as a basis for building a city. (You can also import local terrains into the program\emdash directions for importing USGS maps into }{
\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  are available at the SimCity web site (http://www.simcity.com).) After students have built their cities, have
 them discuss how the cities they built are similar and different from each other. How did they incorporate the terrain into the city plan? If time permits, show students a map of the real city. Have them compare and contrast the cities they built with th
e real city.
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\fs28\cgrid0 Simulation 3: Zoned Out
\par }{\f4\fs24\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 Objectives
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-240\li720\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab To explore the relationship between residential, industrial, and commercial zones.
\par \bullet \tab To compare and contrast the effects of different zone densities.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 The Activity
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par In this simulation, students will run t
hree simulations to compare the demand for different zone types within a city. First, they will use the city they created in Basic Building 101 to observe the population growth within equal-size residential, commercial, and industrial zones over a two-yea
r period (}{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0 
 time). They will find that they need to increase the size of the residential and industrial zones, and decrease the size of the commercial zone to better meet the demands of the city. Next, they will use the population values to try t
o determine a relationship between the demand for different zone types and adjust the size of the three zones to better fit the demands of the city. After calculating the percentage of population in each zone, they will discover that the demand for the di
f
ferent zone types basically follows the relationship residential equals industrial plus commercial (R = I + C). Finally, they will rezone the areas for different densities to observe how zone density affects the overall population of the city. Students wi
ll see that a higher zone density allows more residents to live in a given area.
\par 
\par Have students perform the following actions:
\par 
\par }\pard \fi-360\li360\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 1.\tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Simulation A: }{\f4\cgrid0 Start }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  and load in Basic City (the city from Simulation 1: Basic Building 101). Select the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
Preferences }{\f4\cgrid0 option from the}{\b\f4\cgrid0  Change Settings & Exit }{\f4\cgrid0 Menu. Disable }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Disasters}{\f4\cgrid0 , then click on the checkmark to close the Preferences Window.
\par 
\par 2.\tab Click on the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Run Simulation }{\f4\cgrid0 button to start the simulation. Run the simulation for two years (Sim time), then click on the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Pause Simulation}{\f4\cgrid0  button to pause the simulation.
\par 
\par 3.\tab Scroll around the city. Do all of the squares in all of the zones have buildings on them? If not, which zone or zones contain empty squares?
\par 
\par 4.\tab Examine the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 RCI Indicator}{\f4\cgrid0 . Which zones, if any, are in demand? Which, if any, are not in demand?
\par 
\par 5.\tab Select the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 View Data}{\f4\cgrid0  option from the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Adjust & Review}{\f4\cgrid0  Menu to open the View Data Window. Use the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Graphs}{\f4\cgrid0 
 tool in the View Data Window to view the residential, commercial, industrial, and total city populations over time. On a separate sheet of paper, record the value for each population. 
\par 
\par 6.\tab Use the information you recorded to calculate the following: 
\par \tab \bullet  The percentage of the city size that is residential. (Round to the nearest 10 percent)
\par \tab \bullet  The percentage of the city size that is industrial. (Round to the nearest 10 percent)
\par \tab \bullet  The percentage of the city size that is commercial. (Round to the nearest 10 percent)
\par 
\par 7.\tab Do }{\i\f4\cgrid0 not}{\f4\cgrid0  save your current city.
\par 
\par 8.\tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Simulation B: }{\f4\cgrid0 Reload Basic City, and disable the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Disasters }{\f4\cgrid0 option in the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Preferences }{\f4\cgrid0 Window.
\par 
\par 9.\tab Using the percentages you obtained in Simulation A, rezone your city to match those percentages. For example, if you found 50% of the city population was devoted to resident
ial, rezone your city so that half of the squares are zoned as residential. Do the same for the commercial and industrial sections.
\par 
\par 10.\tab Run the simulation for two years, then click on the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Pause Simulation}{\f4\cgrid0  button to pause the simulation.
\par 
\par 11.\tab Scroll around the city. Do all of the squares in all of the zones have buildings on them? If not, which zone or zones contain empty squares?
\par 
\par 12.\tab Examine the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 RCI Indicator}{\f4\cgrid0 . Which zones, if any, are in demand? Which, if any, are not in demand?
\par 
\par 13.\tab Use the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Graphs}{\f4\cgrid0  tool in the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 View Data}{\f4\cgrid0 
 Window to view the residential, commercial, industrial, and total city populations over time. On a separate sheet of paper, record the value for each population. 
\par 
\par 14.\tab Use the information you recorded to answer the following:
\par \tab \bullet  Compare the resident population of the two simulations. Did the resident population increase, decrease, or stay the same when you rezoned the area?
\par \tab \bullet  Compare the industrial population of the two simulations. Did the industrial population increase, decrease, or stay the same?
\par \tab \bullet  Compare the commercial population of the two simulations. Did the commercial population increase, decrease, or stay the same?
\par \tab \bullet  Compare the total city size of the two simulations. Did the total city size increase, decrease, or stay the same?
\par 
\par 15.\tab  Do }{\i\f4\cgrid0 not}{\f4\cgrid0  save your current city.
\par 
\par 16.\tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Simulation C: }{\f4\cgrid0 Reload Basic City again, and disable the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Disasters }{\f4\cgrid0 option.
\par 
\par 17.\tab Rezone only the residential area as a medium density area.
\par 
\par 18.\tab Run the simulation for two years, then click on the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Pause Simulation}{\f4\cgrid0  button to pause the simulation.
\par 
\par 19.\tab Examine the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 RCI Indicator}{\f4\cgrid0 . Which zones, if any, are in demand? Which, if any, are not in demand?
\par 
\par 20.\tab Use the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Graphs}{\f4\cgrid0  tool in the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 View Data}{\f4\cgrid0  Window to view the residential, commercial, industrial, and total city populations 
over time. On a separate sheet of paper, record the value for each population. 
\par 
\par 21.\tab Use the information you recorded to answer the following:
\par \tab \bullet  Compare the resident population of the Simulation A and this simulation. Did the population increase, decrease, or stay the same when you rezoned the area?
\par \tab \bullet  Compare the industrial population of the Simulation A and this simulation. Did the population increase, decrease, or stay the same?
\par \tab \bullet  Compare the commercial population of the Simulation A and this simulation. Did the population increase, decrease, or stay the same?
\par \tab \bullet  Compare the total city size of the two simulations. Did the total city size increase, decrease, or stay the same when you rezoned the area?
\par 
