\par }{\b\i\f1\fs24\cgrid0 Unit 2\emdash City Services
\par }{\f4\fs24\cgrid0 
\par }{\f1\fs24\cgrid0 Unit Summary
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par In this unit, your students will investigate some of the services a city provides. First, students will compare and contrast different types of power plants for cost effectiveness and pollution produced. Next, they will discover why sanitation services ar
e important in a city. Then students will investigate methods for decreasing crime in a city. Finally, students will investigate ways in which recreational and cultural facilities affect the lives of the citizens within the city.
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs24\cgrid0 Background
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par The developmen
t and growth of a city is totally dependent on the services it provides: utilities, such as power, water, sanitation, and telecommunications; government services, such as law enforcement, fire protection, transportation, and education; and recreational an
d
 cultural services, such as public parks, zoos, museums, and libraries. The availability (or lack thereof) of these services affects the value of land, the desirability of neighborhoods throughout the city, and ultimately, the quality of life in the city.

\par 
\par A city cannot function with utilities. Utilities supply the power to run lights and house appliances, provide clean water for drinking and bathing, or remove the waste materials that can choke a city. As with many things in the real world, there are trade
offs for providing these necessities, including high costs and pollution.
\par 
\par Each type of government service affects a city on many levels. For example, police departments lower the crime rate, which in turn raises property values. Mass transpo
rtation reduces the amount of traffic on the streets, which in turn decreases the amount of pollution in an area. Schools and colleges increase the overall education level of the population, which in turn increases the economic potential of the workforce.
 And parks and recreational facilities provide visual relief and places for play, which increases the overall well-being of the population.
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs24\cgrid0 Jumping In
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par Below are some sample discussion questions to help you get your class talking and thinking city services. Mix, match, tailor, or add questions as you see fit to customize the discussion to your class age and grade.
\par 
\par }\pard \fi-240\li720\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab Name and discuss as many different government services as you can think of. Why do these services exist? What kinds of buildings do they require? Who pays for the services?
\par 
\par \bullet \tab Do you think government services and facilities always have a positive effect on a city? Why or why not? If not, what are some of the negative effects that the service or facility might produce?
\par 
\par \bullet \tab What are utilities? What are the different utilities needed to make a city run?
\par 
\par \bullet \tab If you were running a city and had to choose between a cheap, polluting power plant or an expensive, clean power plant, which would you choose? Why?
\par 
\par \bullet \tab What would happen if there were no garbage collection in your area? How might the lack of sanitation service affect your mood? Your health? The attractiveness and value of the area?
\par 
\par \bullet \tab What are some of the factors that might affect the crime rate in a city? What are some ways in which the crime rate might be reduced?
\par 
\par \bullet \tab Discuss the concept of "quality of life." What types of things contribute or detract from it?
\par 
\par \bullet \tab If you ran a city and wanted to attract people, what types of services and facilities might your supply?
\par 
\par }\pard \fi-240\li240\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\fs28\cgrid0 Simulation 1: Power to the People
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 
\par Objectives
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-240\li720\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab To compare and contrast different types of power plants.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 The Activity
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par In this simulation, students will replace the power plants in an existing city with different kinds of power plants to observe the costs and the effects 
on pollution of each type of power plant. Students will discover that the price per megawatt of non-polluting power plants tends to be higher than that of polluting power plants. They will also discover that in some cases, the number of power plants neede
d to generate enough electricity to power the city is either unreasonable (as in the case of windmills) or more polluting than smaller numbers of power plants that actually generate more pollution per plant (as in the case of gas power plants).
\par 
\par Have students perform the following actions:
\par 
\par }\pard \fi-360\li360\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 1.\tab Start }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  and load Riverland (a Saved City that comes with the program).
\par 
\par 2.\tab Select the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Preferences }{\f4\cgrid0 option from the}{\b\f4\cgrid0  Change Settings & Exit }{\f4\cgrid0 Menu. Disable }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Disasters}{\f4\cgrid0 , then click on the checkmark to close the Preferences Window.
\par 
\par 3.\tab Select the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 View Data}{\f4\cgrid0  option from the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Adjust & Review}{\f4\cgrid0  Menu to open the View Data Window. Click on the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Charts }{\f4\cgrid0 button. Select }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Electricity}{\f4\cgrid0 
. What type of power does this city current use? How much power (in megawatts) is used each year? Based on this number, approximately how much power is used each month?
\par 
\par 4.\tab Open the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Pollution Data }{\f4\cgrid0 Map in the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 View Data }{\f4\cgrid0 Window. Select }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Air Pollution}{\f4\cgrid0  to view the Air Pollution Data Map. Click on }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Use as Map}{\f4\cgrid0 
 to use this map as your Navigation Map.
\par 
\par 5.\tab Use the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Graphs}{\f4\cgrid0  tool in the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 View Data}{\f4\cgrid0  Window to view the pollution level over time. On a separate piece of paper, record the value for pollution over the past year.
\par 
\par 6.\tab Open the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Build Power Plant}{\f4\cgrid0  Menu. Click on each type of power plant to view information about that plant. For each type of power plant listed calculate the following:
\par \tab \bullet \tab The number of this type of power plant required to produce equal or greater amounts of power than is used by the city each month.
\par \tab \bullet \tab The cost of placing this number of power plants.
\par \tab \bullet \tab Whether or not this type of power plant generates pollution.
\par 
\par 7.\tab Locate the two power plants in this city (they are on the Northeast side of the city). Use the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Bulldozer}{\f4\cgrid0  tool to remove the power plants. }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Save}{\f4\cgrid0  this city as PowerCity.
\par 
\par 8.\tab Open the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Power Plant }{\f4\cgrid0 Menu and select the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Coal }{\f4\cgrid0 plant. Place the number of Coal power plants you calculated in Step 6 in the area where the previous power plants used to be.
\par 
\par 9.\tab Run the city for one year (Sim Time). Keep an eye on the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Navigation}{\f4\cgrid0  Map. Is pollution increasing, decreasing, or remaining about the same over time? At the end of a year, }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Pause}{\f4\cgrid0  the simulation.

\par 
\par 10.\tab Use the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Graphs}{\f4\cgrid0  tool in the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 View Data}{\f4\cgrid0  Window to view the pollution level over time. On a separate piece of paper, record the value for pollution over the past year.
\par 
\par 11.\tab Without saving the city, reload PowerCity. Repeat steps 8-10 using }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Oil}{\f4\cgrid0  power plants.
\par 
\par 12.\tab Without saving the city, reload PowerCity. Repeat steps 8-10 using }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Gas}{\f4\cgrid0  power plants.
\par 
\par 13.\tab Without saving the city, reload PowerCity. Repeat steps 8-10 using }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Solar}{\f4\cgrid0  power plants.
\par 
\par 14.\tab Without saving the city, reload PowerCity. Repeat steps 8-10 using }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Fusion}{\f4\cgrid0  power plants.
