\par }{\b\i\f1\fs24\cgrid0 Unit 3\emdash City Management
\par }{\f4\fs24\cgrid0 
\par }{\f1\fs24\cgrid0 Unit Summary
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par In this unit, your students will explore some of the financial and political aspects of city management. First, students will learn how to set tax rates in }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0 
 and will investigate how tax rates affect the city. Next, students will discover what happens when the budget for mass transportation is cut. Then students will examine some of the city ordinances that exist in }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0 
 and analyze the impact of such ordinances. Next, students will study the fiscal and social impact of import and export deals with neighboring cities. Finally, students will explore some of the effects of urban renewal on land value.
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs24\cgrid0 Background
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par The art of city management depends on funding and budgeting. Most of the revenue for cities comes from taxes. Other sources of income include such things as user fees, dividends from investments, special assessments, bonds, sale of properties, and federal
 
grants. This money is then spent on services and building and maintaining the city's infrastructure. In most cities, the city government is bound by law to a balanced budget. The overall goal is to set reasonable tax rates and budget expenditures carefull
y
 so as to make enough surplus to continue growing and expanding, without taxing the citizens, workers, and businesses so much that they leave the area or revolt. The mayor of the city, along with other elected and appointed officials such as supervisors, 
council members, or city managers, determine municipal policies. These policies include such things as zoning, setting tax rates, budgeting, and passing ordinances.
\par 
\par One of the important aspects of city economics is land value. The value of land determines 
the both the types of buildings that can be built in an area and the amount of taxes generated by that area. Many things affect land value, including transportation access, crime, pollution, population density, and proximity to open spaces, bodies of wate
r, and amenities. When an area declines in value, the city may step in and implement urban redevelopment or renewal programs to help rehabilitate the area.
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs24\cgrid0 Jumping In
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par Below are some sample discussion questions to help you get your class talking and thinking about city management. Mix, match, tailor, or add questions as you see fit to customize the discussion to your class age and grade.
\par 
\par }\pard \fi-240\li720\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab How does a city get money? Who decides what that money is spent on?
\par 
\par \bullet \tab What are taxes? Why are taxes important? How are they collected? How are they used?
\par 
\par \bullet \tab What types of taxes are there? How are these taxes different?
\par 
\par \bullet \tab What is a budget? What does it mean to "balance the budget"?
\par 
\par \bullet \tab What are some of the things that might happen if a city's budget doesn't properly cover city services?
\par 
\par \bullet \tab What is mass transportation? What are some of the advantages and disadvantages of this form of transportation?
\par 
\par \bullet \tab What is a strike? Is a strike an effective method for letting government officials know how people feel about those officials' decisions? Why or why not?
\par 
\par \bullet \tab What are laws and ordinances? Who invents them? Who approves them?
\par 
\par \bullet \tab In addition to the effects of terrain, why might different areas of cities have different land values?
\par 
\par \bullet \tab What is urban renewal? What role does the government play in urban renewal programs?
\par 
\par 
\par }\pard \fi-240\li240\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\fs28\cgrid0 Simulation 1: "Show Me the Money!"
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 
\par Objectives
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-240\li720\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab To investigate how tax rates affect the citizens of a city and the city budget.
\par \bullet \tab To observe how people react to government decisions.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 The Activity
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par In this simulation, students will compare and contrast what happens to the budget and population of a city as residential taxes change. First they will run a simulation for two years (Sim time) with a residential tax rate of
 7%. Next, they will rerun the simulation with a residential tax rate of 0%. Finally, they will run the simulation with a residential tax rate of 20%. Students will discover that when tax rates are low, the population of the city increases, and the income
 
of the city decreases. When tax rates are high, the population of the city decreases, and the income of the city increases. However, if the tax rates are too high, the residents may move out (or never immigrate in), and the tax base of the city will be lo
wer than that of the same city with lower taxes, causing the overall income of the city to decrease.
\par 
\par Have students perform the following actions:
\par 
\par }\pard \fi-360\li360\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 1.\tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Simulation A: }{\f4\cgrid0 Start }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  and load Clocktower Center (a Starter Town that comes with the program).
\par 
\par 2.\tab Select the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Preferences }{\f4\cgrid0 option from the}{\b\f4\cgrid0  Change Settings & Exit }{\f4\cgrid0 Menu. Disable }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Disasters}{\f4\cgrid0 , then click on the checkmark to close the Preferences Window.
\par 
\par 3.\tab Run the simulation for two years (Sim time), then click on the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Pause Simulation}{\f4\cgrid0  button to pause the simulation.
\par 
\par 4.\tab Select the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 View Data}{\f4\cgrid0  option from the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Adjust & Review}{\f4\cgrid0  Menu to open the View Data Window. Use the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Graphs}{\f4\cgrid0 
 tool in the View Data Window to view the residential, commercial, industrial, and total city population over time. On a separate piece of paper, record the value for each population.
\par 
\par 5.\tab Select the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Budget }{\f4\cgrid0 option from the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Adjust & Review}{\f4\cgrid0  Menu to open the Budget Window. Record the current funds, total income, and total expenditures for the year. If necessary, click on the }{
\b\f4\cgrid0 Income }{\f4\cgrid0 button. Record the amount of annual income from Residential taxes, Industry taxes, and Commerce taxes. Is the total income from taxes equal to, less than, or greater than the total annual expenditures?
\par 
\par 6.\tab Do not save this simulation.
\par 
\par 7.\tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Simulation B: }{\f4\cgrid0 Reload Clocktower Center. Make sure the disaster preference is disabled.
\par 
\par 8.\tab Select the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Budget }{\f4\cgrid0 option from the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Adjust & Review}{\f4\cgrid0  Menu to open the Budget Window. If necessary, click on the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Income }{\f4\cgrid0 
button. Use the down arrow to set the Residential taxes to }{\b\f4\cgrid0 0}{\f4\cgrid0 . Close the Budget Window.
\par 
\par 9.\tab Repeat Steps 3-5.
\par 
\par 10.\tab Do not save this simulation.
\par 
\par 11.\tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Simulation C: }{\f4\cgrid0 Reload Clocktower Center. Make sure the disaster preference is disabled.
\par 
\par 12.\tab Select the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Budget }{\f4\cgrid0 option from the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Adjust & Review}{\f4\cgrid0  Menu to open the Budget Window. If necessary, click on the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Income }{\f4\cgrid0 
button. Use the up arrow to set the Residential taxes to }{\b\f4\cgrid0 20}{\f4\cgrid0 . Close the Budget Window.
\par 
\par 13.\tab Repeat Steps 3-5.
\par 
\par 14.\tab Do not save this simulation.
\par 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 FOLLOW UP}{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 : }{\f4\cgrid0 Have the students use the information they recorded to answer the following questions:
\par }\pard \fi-240\li240\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab 
How does lowering residential taxes to 0% affect the total income the city receives? How does it affect the residential population of the city? How does it affect the overall population of the city?
\par \bullet \tab How does raising residential taxes to 20% affect the total income the city receives? How does it affect the residential population of the city? How does it affect the overall population of the city?
\par \bullet \tab Is it possible that raising taxes could actually decrease the overall income of the city? Why or why not?
\par \bullet \tab Are the budgets in any of the three simulations balanced? Why or why not? If not, what would you need to do in each simulation to balance the budget?
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 Extensions
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-240\li240\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab To study the effects of taxes on industry and city developme
nt, have students repeat the simulation keeping residential and commercial taxes steady while varying industrial taxes. To study the effects of taxes on commerce and city development, have students repeat the simulation keeping residential and industrial 
taxes steady while varying commercial taxes.
\par 
\par \bullet \tab Have students research the tax rates in your area. What types of taxes exist in residential areas? What are the rates? What types of taxes exist for industrial areas? What are the rates? What types of taxes ex
ist in commercial areas? What are the rates?
\par 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f4\fs28\cgrid0 Simulation 2: Three Strikes, You're Out!
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 
\par Objectives
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-240\li720\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab To observe what happens when funding for a city service is cut.
\par \bullet \tab To explore ways in which to end a strike in }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0 .
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 The Activity
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par In this simula
tion, students eliminate the funding for mass transportation in an already established city. They will then observe the effects on traffic, moral, and the city budget. Next they will experiment with different ways in which to end the strike that occurs wh
en a service is underfunded.
\par 
\par Have students perform the following actions:
\par 
\par }\pard \fi-360\li360\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 1.\tab Start }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  and load SimIsle (a Saved City that comes with the program).
\par 
\par 2.\tab Select the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Preferences }{\f4\cgrid0 option from the}{\b\f4\cgrid0  Change Settings & Exit }{\f4\cgrid0 Menu. Disable }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Disasters}{\f4\cgrid0 , then click on the checkmark to close the Preferences Window.
\par 
\par 3.\tab Move around the City View Window. What types of transportation are available in this city? Which of these, if any, are forms of mass transportation?
\par 
\par 4.\tab Select the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 View Data}{\f4\cgrid0  option from the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Adjust & Review}{\f4\cgrid0  Menu to open the View Data Window. Select the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Traffic and Transportation Data}{\f4\cgrid0 
 Map. In general, would you describe the traffic in this city as light, medium, heavy, or very heavy? Click on the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Use as Map}{\f4\cgrid0  button\emdash the traffic map will replace t
he current Navigation Map so you can easily refer to it as you run the simulation.
\par 
\par 5.\tab Click on }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Graphs}{\f4\cgrid0  in the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 View Data}{\f4\cgrid0  Window. View the graphs for city size and traffic. In general, has the traffic increased, decreased, or remained about the same for the past year?
\par 
\par 6.\tab Select the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Budget }{\f4\cgrid0 option from the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Adjust & Review}{\f4\cgrid0  Menu to open the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Budget}{\f4\cgrid0  Window. If necessary, click on the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Expenditures}{\f4\cgrid0 
 button. What is the current annual funding for mass transit? What are the total current annual expenditures for the city? What percentage of the total expenditures is devoted to mass transit?
\par 
\par 7.\tab Slide the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Mass Transit}{\f4\cgrid0  funds slider to the far left. This will set the funding for mass transit to zero.
\par 
\par 8.\tab Run the simulation for one year. Keep an eye on the news ticker. Click on any stories that relate to traffic and transportation, and record how the Sims react when funding is cut. Also keep
 an eye on the Navigation Map. In general, does traffic increase, decrease, or stay about the same after the funding is cut? At the end of the year, }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Pause}{\f4\cgrid0  the simulation.
\par 
\par 9.\tab Open the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 View Data }{\f4\cgrid0 Window and click on }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Graphs}{\f4\cgrid0 . View the graphs for city size and 
traffic. In general, has the traffic increased, decreased, or remained about the same for the past year? Has the city population increased, decreased, or remained about the same for the past year?
\par 
\par 10.\tab Open the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Meet }{\f4\cgrid0 Window. Double-click on any items relate
d to transportation and traffic to read those items. Is one of the items about a transit strike? If so, what reasons are given for the strike? What demands are the transit workers asking for in order to end the strike? Close the window without accepting o
r rejecting the strikers demands.
\par 
\par 11.\tab If your transit workers have gone on strike, the following are some possible methods for dealing with the situation. Predict the positive and negative effects of each method. Then select one to test.
\par \tab \bullet \tab Allow the strike to continue without increasing funding for the year.
\par \tab \bullet \tab Increase funding to its original prestrike level.
\par \tab \bullet \tab Meet the demands of the striking workers.
\par \tab \bullet \tab Bulldoze every building associated with mass transit, which effectively fires everyone in that \tab department.
\par 
\par 12.\tab Design an experiment to test your prediction. Then make the necessary changes to implement your test. Record the amount of money you spend making those changes.
\par 
\par 13.\tab Run the simulation for another year, then pause the simulation.
\par 
\par 14.\tab Open the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Meet }{\f4\cgrid0 
Window. Read any items related to traffic or transportation. Which of the following best describes the current situation: a) the workers are still on strike, b) the workers are back to work, but mass transportation is still underfunded, or c) the wor
kers are back to work and mass transportation is well funded?
\par 
\par 15.\tab Open the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 View Data }{\f4\cgrid0 Window and click on }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Graphs}{\f4\cgrid0 . View the graphs for city size and traffic. In general, has the traffic increased, decreased, or remained about the same for the past year? Has
 the city population increased, decreased, or remained about the same for the past year?
\par 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 FOLLOW UP}{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 : }{\f4\cgrid0 Have the students use the information they recorded to answer the following questions:
\par }\pard \fi-240\li240\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab Did lack of funding for mass transportation affect traffic in the city? How?
\par \bullet \tab Did lack of funding for mass transportation affect the population of the city? How?
\par \bullet \tab Which method did you choose to use to deal with the strike? How effective was the method at ending the strike? How effective was the method at improving traffic?
\par \bullet \tab How much money did you spend trying to end the strike? What is the difference in the amount of money you spent and the annual amount money spent on mass transportation before the strike?
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 Extension
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-240\li240\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab 
Locate a copy of your town's budget. Have students enter the data into a spreadsheet program. Assign different students as lobbyists for each item in the budget. Then have a "budget committee meeting," where you or another student tries to reduce city sp
ending. As each item is considered, have the student lobbyist for that item argue why the funding for his or her item should remain intact. 
\par }\pard \fi-360\li360\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\fs28\cgrid0 Simulation 3: Laying Down the Law
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 
\par Objectives
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-240\li720\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab To introduce the concept of ordinances.
\par \bullet \tab To investigate the effects of ordinances on a city.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 The Activity
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par In this simulation, students will examine some of the city ordinances that exist in }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0 , and predict the positive and negative effects of each one. Then they will devise an experiment to test their predi
ctions for one of the ordinances.
\par 
\par Have students perform the following actions:
\par 
\par }\pard \fi-360\li360\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 1.\tab Start }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  and load Suburbia (a Starter Town that comes with the program).
\par 
\par 2.\tab Select the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Ordinances }{\f4\cgrid0 option from the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Adjust & Review}{\f4\cgrid0  Menu to open the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Ordinances}{\f4\cgrid0  Window. Click on the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Advisor}{\f4\cgrid0 
 button for each department to be taken to the Advisor for that department. Read through the information on each ordinance. What are the positive and negative effects of each ordinance? Based on what you read, decide whether or not
 you might pass each ordinance. Record your answers on a separate piece of paper.
\par 
\par 3.\tab Select one of the ordinances from your list. Predict the effects of passing the ordinance on the following:
\par \tab \bullet \tab power or water consumption
\par \tab \bullet \tab garbage production
\par \tab \bullet \tab public safety
\par \tab \bullet \tab health and/or education
\par \tab \bullet \tab traffic
\par \tab \bullet \tab pollution
\par \tab \bullet \tab population growth
\par \tab \bullet \tab city income
\par \tab \bullet \tab city expenditures
\par 
\par 4.\tab Design an experiment to test your predictions. Include which factors you need to watch during the test, and which factors will be controls.
\par 
\par 5.\tab Run your experiment. Record your results.
\par 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 FOLLOW UP}{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 : }{\f4\cgrid0 Have the students use the information they recorded to answer the following questions:
\par }\pard \fi-240\li240\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab Did your experiment support your predictions? Why or why not?
\par \bullet \tab How might your test be changed to make it more accurate?
\par \bullet \tab How do people test ordinances in real cities?
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 Extension
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-240\li240\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab Locate a voter information pamphlet for a recent or upcoming local election. Assign two (or more) students to research one of the laws or ordinances. Have students debate t
he pros and cons of each issue in class, and then have the class vote on the issues.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-360\li360\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\fs28\cgrid0 Simulation 4: Let's Make a Deal
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 
\par Objectives
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-240\li720\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab To learn about the fiscal impact of import and export deals with neighboring cities.
\par \bullet \tab To learn how to connect with neighboring cities in }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0 .
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 The Activity
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par In this simulation, students will first connect with a neighboring city to arrange for possible deals involving garbage disposal. Then they will run the simulation until they h
ave excess or insufficient resources, and the neighbor offers a trade deal (deals can only be initiated by the neighboring city or cities). Once a deal is offered, students will save the game. Next, they will run the simulation twice, once after accepting
 the deal and once without accepting the deal, and compared the results of the two simulations.
\par 
\par Have students perform the following actions:
\par 
\par }\pard \fi-360\li360\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 1.\tab Start }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  and load Suburbia (a starter town that comes with the program). Select the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Preferences }{\f4\cgrid0 option from the}{
\b\f4\cgrid0  Change Settings & Exit }{\f4\cgrid0 Menu. Disable }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Disasters}{\f4\cgrid0 , then click on the checkmark to close the Preferences Window.
\par 
\par 2.\tab Use the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Road }{\f4\cgrid0 tool to extend the road at the south-east end of the city all the way to the south-east edge of the map. When the dialo
g box pops up asking if you want to connect to the neighboring city, record the price of the connection, then click on }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Yes}{\f4\cgrid0 . 
\par 
\par 3.\tab Click on }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Run Simulation}{\f4\cgrid0  to start the simulation. Keep an eye on the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 News Ticker}{\f4\cgrid0 
 in the Information Bar. When you see a news item regarding a possible trade deal with your neighbor, pause the simulation. (Note: If a news items does not appear within the first year, pause the simulation and open the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Meet}{\f4\cgrid0 
 Window to see if any deals have been offered.)
\par 
\par 4.\tab Open the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Meet }{\f4\cgrid0 Window. You should see the deal (or deals) the neighbor is proposing in the window. Double-click on a deal to get more information about the deal.
\par 
\par 5.\tab Record the following information about the deal:
\par \tab \bullet \tab Does the deal involve export (your city is selling a service to the other city) or import (your city is \tab buying a service from the other city)?
\par \tab \bullet \tab How much of the item will be imported or exported each month?
\par \tab \bullet \tab How much will you have to pay or be paid each month?
\par \tab \bullet \tab What is the penalty if you terminate the deal early?
\par \tab \bullet \tab What are the possible advantages and disadvantages of accepting the deal? Declining the deal?
\par 
\par 6.\tab Close the window without accepting or rejecting the deal. Then save this city as NewDealCity.
\par 
\par 7.\tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Simulation A: }{\f4\cgrid0 Restart the simulation. Open the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Meet }{\f4\cgrid0 Window. Double-click on the deal. Then click on }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Reject}{\f4\cgrid0  to reject the deal.
\par 
\par 8.\tab Run the city for a year, then pause the simulation. Select the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Budget }{\f4\cgrid0 option from the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Adjust & Review}{\f4\cgrid0  Menu to open the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Budget}{\f4\cgrid0 
 Window and record the following information:
\par 
\par \tab \bullet \tab If the deal was for import: The total year end income and the amount of income from neighbors.
\par \tab \bullet \tab If the deal was for export: The total year end expenditures and the amount of expenditures to \tab neighbors.
\par 
\par 9.\tab Open the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 View Data}{\f4\cgrid0  Window and click on the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Charts }{\f4\cgrid0 button. Then click on }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Garbage}{\f4\cgrid0 . Record the total amount of garbage produced annually.
\par 
\par 10.\tab Do not save this city.
\par 
\par 11.\tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Simulation B: }{\f4\cgrid0 Reload NewDealCity. Open the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Meet }{\f4\cgrid0 Window. Double-click on the deal. Then click on }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Accept}{\f4\cgrid0  to accept the deal.
\par 
\par 12.\tab Run the simulation for a year, then pause the simulation. Select the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Budget }{\f4\cgrid0 option from the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Adjust & Review}{\f4\cgrid0  Menu to open the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Budget}{\f4\cgrid0 
 Window and record the following information:
\par 
\par \tab \bullet \tab If the deal was for import: The total year end income and the amount of income from neighbors.
\par \tab \bullet \tab If the deal was for export: The total year end expenditures and the amount of expenditures to \tab neighbors.
\par 
\par 13.\tab Open the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 View Data}{\f4\cgrid0  Window and click on the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Charts }{\f4\cgrid0 button. Then click on }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Garbage}{\f4\cgrid0 .
 Record the total amount of garbage produced annually. If the deal was for import, how much of that garbage comes for the neighboring city? If the deal was for export, how much of the garbage goes to the neighboring city?
\par 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 FOLLOW UP}{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 : }{\f4\cgrid0 Have the students use the information they recorded to answer the following questions:
\par }\pard \fi-240\li240\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab Assume the deal you made lasts for five years. How much will you make or spend on the deal during that time? How much extra garbage will you import or export during that time?
\par \bullet \tab Does the deal you made make fiscal sense? Why or why not?
\par \bullet \tab What other elements in the city might be affected by the deal you made?
\par \bullet \tab What are some other possible solutions you might have tried to either generate income or decrease the amount of garbage in your area?
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 Extension
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-240\li240\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab Have the students investigate other types of neighborhood deals by connecting power lines and/or water pipes with a neighboring city. Then have them repeat the simulation.
\par \bullet \tab Have the students read through some of the local business deals that are offered by petitioners in the program. Which deals would they make? Why?
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-360\li360\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\fs28\cgrid0 Simulation 5: Everything Old is New Again
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 
\par Objectives
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-240\li720\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab To investigate the effects of urban renewal on land value.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 The Activity
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par In this simulation, students will open a preexisting game in }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0 
, knock down old buildings in a residential area, and then experiment with three different ways of changing the land value of that area: adding recreational and
/or cultural facilities, rezoning the area to a higher density, and rezoning the area for a different use.
\par 
\par Have students perform the following actions:
\par }{\f17\fs24\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-360\li360\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 1.\tab Start }{\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\f4\cgrid0  and load Riverland (a Saved City that comes with the program. Select the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Preferences }{\f4\cgrid0 option from the}{\b\f4\cgrid0 
 Change Settings & Exit }{\f4\cgrid0 Menu. Disable }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Disasters}{\f4\cgrid0 , then click on the checkmark to close the Preferences Window.
\par 
\par 2.\tab Use the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Query}{\f4\cgrid0  Tool or the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Layer Views}{\f4\cgrid0  tool to locate a residential area of low land value and of low or medium density. Th
en zoom in and view the different buildings in the area. In general, what type of buildings exist? Do they look run down or clean? Are there any abandoned buildings? Would you want to live in this area?
\par 
\par 3.\tab Select the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Bulldozer}{\f4\cgrid0  tool and bulldoze all the buildings in that area.
\par 
\par 4.\tab Save the game as NewRiverland.
\par 
\par 5.\tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Simulation A}{\f4\cgrid0 : Add a few parks, fountains, playgrounds, historic buildings
, or anything else you think the Sims might like to the area that you bulldozed in Step 3. Run the simulation for one year (SimTime), then pause the game.
\par 
\par 6.\tab Use the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Query}{\f4\cgrid0  Tool or the}{\b\f4\cgrid0  Layer View}{\f4\cgrid0  tool to check the land value of the area. In general, is the land value higher, lower, or the same as before?
\par 
\par 7.\tab Zoom in and view the different buildings in the area. In general, what type of buildings exist? Do they look run down or clean? Are there any abandoned buildings? Would you want to live in this area? Why or why not?
\par 
\par 8.\tab Do not save this city.
\par 
\par 9.\tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Simulation B}{\f4\cgrid0 : Reload NewRiverland. Rezone the bulldozed area for a higher density\emdash that is, if it was a medium density section, zone it as a high densi
ty section. Or if it was a low density section, zone it as a medium or high density section. Run the simulation for one year (SimTime), then pause the game.
\par 
\par 10.\tab Use the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Query}{\f4\cgrid0  Tool or the}{\b\f4\cgrid0  Layer View}{\f4\cgrid0  tool to check the land value of the area. In general, is the land value higher, lower, or the same as before?
\par 
\par 11.\tab Zoom in and view the different buildings in the area. In general, what type of buildings exist? Do they look run down or clean? Are there any abandoned buildings? Would you want to live in this area? Why or why not?
\par 
\par 12.\tab Do not save this city.
\par 
\par 13.\tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Simulation C}{\f4\cgrid0 : Reload NewRiverland. Rezone the bulldozed area for commercial or industrial use. Run the simulation for one year (SimTime), then pause the game.
\par 
\par 14.\tab Use the }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Query}{\f4\cgrid0  Tool or the}{\b\f4\cgrid0  Layer View}{\f4\cgrid0  tool to check the land value of the area. In general, is the land value higher, lower, or the same as before?
\par 
\par 15.\tab Zoom in and view the different buildings in the area. In general, what type of buildings exist? Do they look run down or clean? Are there any abandoned buildings? Would you want to live near this area? Why or why not?
\par 
\par 16.\tab Do not save this city.
\par 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 FOLLOW UP}{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 : }{\f4\cgrid0 Have the students use the information they recorded to answer the following questions:
\par }\pard \fi-240\li240\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab Did adding recreation facilities change the land value? Why or why not?
\par \bullet \tab Did rezoning the area for a higher density change the land value? Why or why not?
\par \bullet \tab Did rezoning the area for a different use change the land value? Why or why not?
\par \bullet \tab Why might a city want to try to increase the land value of an area through urban renewal?
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 Extension
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-240\li240\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \bullet \tab  Have students research the concept of historical preservation. What happens when a building or area is labeled an historical site? What types of buildi
ngs or places are preserved? Does it cost money? Ask students to choose a building in their area as a possible historical site. Then divide the class into two groups, and have one side argue the pros of preserving the site, while the other side argues the
 cons.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f1\fs28\cgrid0 Part 3: Blackline Masters and Resources
\par }{\b\i\f1\fs24\cgrid0 City Planning and Design
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\fs28\cgrid0 Simulation 1: Basic Building 101
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f17\fs24\cgrid0 
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 BEGIN THE GAME
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 1.\tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Start }{\b\i\f4\cgrid0 SimCity 3000}{\b\f4\cgrid0 .
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par \tab You can make skip the opening movie by clicking the mouse button while the movie is playing.
\par 
\par 2.\tab The first screen you'll see is the Opening Menu screen. From here you can choose to start a new city, load a saved city, load a starter town, or load real-world terrain. 
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 \tab To start a new game, click on START NEW CITY.
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par 3.\tab Now you'll see the New City Options screen. From here, you can choose a difficulty level\emdash 
easy, medium, or hard. You can also decide the year in which to start your city and the city size (the total number of tiles in the city). For this activity, you're going to use the easy game option, and build a 
small city with a start date of the year 2000.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f5\fs18\cf6\cgrid0 Art02:NewCityOptions
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \qc\fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par \tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Make sure the EASY game option is selected. Then select a start date of 2000 and the}{\b\f17\cgrid0  }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
SMALL city size. Type in the City Name of BASIC CITY and your name in the Mayor Name box. Once your city options are set, click on the checkmark.
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par 4.\tab The next screen you'll see is the Terrain Selection screen. This screen lets you pick the terrain for your
 city. Clicking on any of the four edges of the Pick Features Map cycles between a coastline and a neighbor border. Clicking on the Map Center of the Pick Features map cycles between dry land, rivers, lake, and a mountain. You can use the sliders to incre
ase or decrease the amount of mountains, water, and trees in the area. If you make any adjustments to the map, you must first click on Re-Generate Terrain to display the new map.
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 \tab For now, click on ACCEPT THIS TERRAIN to accept the current terrain.
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 SELECT AN AREA TO BUILD}{\f4\fs24\cgrid0 
\par }{\f17\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 1.\tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Let's start by getting oriented in the area.}{\f4\cgrid0  }{\b\f4\cgrid0 To do this,}{\f4\cgrid0  }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
take a look the Navigation Map in the View Panel at the bottom-right of the screen.}{\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f5\fs18\cf6\cgrid0 Art03:NavigationMap 
\par }\pard \qc\fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par \tab The Navigation Map lets you see your whole city, instead of just part of it. The red rectangle shows what part of the city you are seeing in the City View Window.
\par 
\par 2.\tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Click on a land area in the Navigation Map\emdash you'll see you automatically move to that area in the City View Window. Move around until you find a large, open area in which to build your city.
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par \tab Note: You can also use your mouse to move around the City View Window\emdash just click and hold the right mouse button. Then move the mouse in the direction you wish to scroll. To center your view on your cursor, click once usin
g the left mouse button.
\par 
\par 3.\tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Zoom in one level using the ZOOM IN button in the View Panel. }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 SET UP ZONES AND ROADS}{\f4\cgrid0 
\par 
\par 1.\tab As you can see, your city is just a bunch of dirt and water right now, so let's start by establishing some zones\emdash places where your Sims can live, work, and shop.
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 \tab Click on the ZONE button [icon] on the Main Toolbar. A menu of zoning buttons will pop up. Click and hold the RESIDENTIAL button. You'll see a submenu of zone densities appear. Move the cursor to highlight
 Light Residential. Then release the mouse button.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f5\fs18\cf6\cgrid0 Art04:LightResidential
\par }\pard \qc\fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par \tab Residential areas are where your Sims live. The density of the area determines what types of houses can be built (such a single-family homes or apartment buildings), and the total number of Sims that can possibly live in that area.
\par 
\par 2.\tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Move the cursor to t
he City View Window. Click and hold on a tile within the area. Then move the cursor to drag out a square residential zone that is 8 tiles long and 9 tiles wide. Release the mouse button to create the zone. (If you change your mind about the placement of t
he zone }{\b\i\f4\cgrid0 before}{\b\f4\cgrid0  you finish placing it, you can cancel the action by holding down the SHIFT key as you release the mouse button.)}{\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f5\fs18\cf6\cgrid0 Art05:PlaceLtResZone
\par }\pard \qc\fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par 
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \tab Notice that creating the zone cost you money\emdash the Fund in the Information Bar is now less than $50,000. Yo
u can use this indicator to keep help track of how much you're spending (or making) on your city.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f5\fs18\cf6\cgrid0 Art06:InfoBarFund
\par }\pard \qc\fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par \tab You also can't move zones once you've placed them\emdash the only way to get rid of them is to use the De-Zone tool. Using this tool costs you m
oney, plus you have to pay again to rezone the area, so it pays to think things through before placing a zone.
\par 
\par 3.\tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Click and hold the COMMERCIAL button, and select Light Commercial from the submenu. Place an 8 x 9 commercial zone next to the long side of the residential zone. The commercial zone is where Sims will build shops and offices.}{
\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f5\fs18\cf6\cgrid0 Art07:PlaceComZone  
\par }\pard \qc\fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 4.\tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Click and hold the INDUSTRIAL button, and select Light Industrial from the submenu. Place an 8 x 9 industrial zone next to the long side of the c
ommercial zone. This industrial zone is where Sims will build factories, industries, and warehouses.}{\f4\cgrid0 
\par 
\par \tab You should now have a layout that looks like the following:
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f5\fs18\cf6\cgrid0 Art08:CurrentLayout
\par }\pard \qc\fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 5.\tab Now that you've provided an area in which your Sims can build, you need to add a way for them to get around.
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 \tab Click on the BUILD TRANSPORTATION button [icon] on the Main Toolbar. A menu of transportation buttons will pop up. Click on the ROAD button to select the Road tool.
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par 6.\tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
Move the cursor to the City View Window. Click and drag to create a road along one side of the zoned area. Add additional roads to form a rectangle around the zoned area. Then add a single long road that runs through the middle of all three zones, as show
n.}{\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f5\fs18\cf6\cgrid0 Art09: AddRoad 
\par }\pard \qc\fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 SET UP UTILITIES
\par 
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 1.\tab There are several utilities that are essential to your Sims' lives\emdash power, water, and garbage disposal. Let's start by adding a source of power to the area.
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 \tab Click on the BUILD UTILITIES button [icon] on the Main Toolbar. A menu of utilities buttons will pop up. Click on the POWER PLANTS button to open the Power Plants Window.
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par \tab The Power Plants Window contains a selection of different power plants. Because this city started in the year 2000, you'll have a large sele
ction of plants from which to choose. If you had started this city in an earlier year, you'd have a very limited selection.
\par 
\par 2.}{\b\f4\cgrid0 \tab Select the SOLAR plant and click the checkmark to close the window. Move the cursor to the City View Window near your zoned area. Place the power plant by clicking on a tile just slightly away from your industrial zone.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f5\fs18\cf6\cgrid0 Art10: AddSolarPlant 
\par }\pard \qc\fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par 
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 \tab }{\f4\cgrid0 Normally Sims don't like living near power plants (would you?), but for this simulation the actual location of the power plant is not important.
\par 
\par 3.}{\b\f4\cgrid0 \tab }{\f4\cgrid0 Next you need to run wires from the power plant to the zones.
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par \tab Select on the POWER LINES button from the BUILD UTILITIES button menu. Click and drag to draw a line of wires from the power plant to at least one point in any of your zones. 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f5\fs18\cf6\cgrid0 Art11:AddPowerLines
\par }\pard \qc\fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par 
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 \tab Note that you only need to place a power line in one of your zones\emdash any building or zone placed within two tiles of an already powered building or zone automatically gets power.
\par 
\par 4.\tab Now let's add a water supply to the area.
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 \tab Select on the WATER STRUCTURES button from the BUILD UTILITIES button menu. This will open the Water Structures Window. Select the WATER PUMPING STATION and click the checkmark to close the window. 
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 \tab Water Pumping Stations hold and pump water to your city. The catch is that they must be placed within two tiles of fresh water in order to work. Luckily you have a nice river full of fresh water in this area.
\par 
\par \tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Move the cursor to the City View Window next to the river in the middle of the area. Place the pumping station by clicking on a tile along the river.}{\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f5\fs18\cf6\cgrid0 Art12:AddPumpStation
\par }\pard \qc\fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par 
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 5.\tab To get the water from the pumping station, you need to add water pipes.
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 \tab Select on the WATER PIPES button from the BUILD UTILITIES button menu. 
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par \tab You'll see that after you select the Water Pipes tool, the view of your city changes\emdash 
you are now looking at the Underground View of your city. This view shows you all of the structures that are providing water, as well as how your pipes are laid out.
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 6.\tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Click and drag to draw a line of pipe from the water pumping station to your zones. If necessary, add additional pipes off the main pipe so that all the tiles in the city are within seven tiles of any part of a pipe.

\par 
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 7.\tab Pumping stations also need power in order to run. To add power lines, you need to return to the regular City View Window.}{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par 
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 \tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Click on the LAYER VIEWS button in the Information Toolbar at the bottom of the window. Click on the DEFAULT VIEW button in the View City Layers Window. Then click on the checkmark to return to the abo
ve ground view of the your city.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f5\fs18\cf6\cgrid0 Art13:CityLayersWindow
\par }\pard \qc\fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 8.}{\b\f4\cgrid0 \tab Select on the POWER LINES button from the BUILD UTILITIES button menu. Click and drag to draw a line of wires from the power plant to your pumping station. 
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 
\par 9.\tab Next, let's add a way for your Sims to get rid of all the garbage they produce as they go about their daily lives.
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 \tab Click on the ZONES button, and then click on the LANDFILL button from the Zones button menu. Locate some land near your zoned area that is also next to a road (garbage truck
s need a way to get to the landfill). Click and drag to create a 2 x 2 zone for your landfill.}{\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f5\fs18\cf6\cgrid0 Art14:AddLandfill
\par }\pard \qc\fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 SAVE YOUR CITY}{\f4\fs24\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\tx5520\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 1.\tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Before you watch your city develop, you need to save this city for f
uture use. To do this, click on the CHANGE SETTINGS & EXIT button, then click on the SAVE button to open the Save City Window. When asked to name the game, type in BASIC CITY. Then click on the checkmark to save your game.}{\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 BRING YOUR CITY TO LIFE}{\f4\fs24\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par 1.\tab Now that you've set up your city, it's time to bring it to life.
\par 
\par \tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Click on the RUN SIMULATION button in the Information Bar to turn the simulation on. Adjust the speed at which the simulation runs by clicking on the SIMULATION SPEED CONTROL button. You can se
e how much time has passed by looking at the DATE indicator on the Information Bar. 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f5\fs18\cf6\cgrid0 Art15:SimSpeedControlButton
\par }\pard \qc\fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par 
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 \tab }{\f4\cgrid0 You can also pause the simulation again at any time by clicking on the PAUSE SIMULATION button in the Information Bar.}{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par 
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 2.\tab To protect your Sims from harm as your city is developing, you should make sure that no disasters occur during the game.
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 \tab Click on the CHANGE SETTINGS & EXIT button, then select the PREFERENCES button to open the Preferences Window. Click on the button next to the DISASTERS option to disable the Disasters option. Then click on the checkmark.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f5\fs18\cf6\cgrid0 Art16:PreferencesWindow
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \qc\fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\f4\fs24\cgrid0 TAKE A LOOK AROUND}{\f4\fs24\cgrid0 
\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\cgrid0 
\par 1.\tab  Let's take a look at how your city is developing.}{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par 
\par \tab 
Use your cursor or the Navigation Map to move around the City View Window. You'll see that Sims are busily building and moving into homes, offices, and factories. Click on the ZOOM IN button in the View Panel to get a closer look at the Sims themselves.}{
\f4\cgrid0 
\par 
\par 2.\tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 To get detailed information about your city, click on the ADJUST & REVIEW button in the Main Toolbar. Then select the QUERY button from the button menu. Click on different areas of your city with the Query tool\emdash 
you'll get lots information about the building or area. When you're done looking at the information, close the Query Window by clicking on the checkmark in the lower right corner.}{\f4\cgrid0 
\par  
\par 3.\tab You can also get detailed information about your city as a whole using the View Data Tool. 
\par 
\par \tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 Select the VIEW DATA
 button from the ADJUST & REVIEW button menu. When the View Data Window opens, click on the different View Data Map buttons on the left. These maps show how specific areas of your city are functioning. When you're done looking at the information, close th
e window by clicking on the checkmark in the lower right corner.
\par 
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 4.\tab To learn more about the wants and needs of the citizens of your city, you'll want to talk to the city advisors. The advisors will give you up-to-the-minute information on issues relating to their departments. 
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 \tab Click on the MEET button to open the Advisors and Petitioners Window. You'll see there are seven Advisors. Select the Advisor you wish to meet by clicking on his or her picture in the top half of the Advisors and Petitioners Window.

\par 
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 \tab You'll see that each advisor has a list of relevant News Topics, Briefings, and Ordinances he or she can discuss with you. 
\par }{\b\f4\cgrid0 
\par \tab Choose the type of information you wish to discuss from the selection box, then select from the list of relevant topics by double clicking on a message. Close the Window by clicking on the X at the top right corner.
\par 
\par }{\f4\cgrid0 5.\tab }{\b\f4\cgrid0 When you have finished exploring your city, exit the game by clicking on the EXIT button from the CHANGE SETTINGS & EXIT button menu. You will be asked if you want
 to save your current city. Click on NO to exit the game. 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f4\fs24\cgrid0 
\par 
